"""
MKT Christ Commentary — John chapters 17–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-john-17-18.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json (chapters 17–18; key tokens: egō eimi G1510, hagiazō G37,
  doxa G1391, basileia G932, alētheia G225)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/parallels/john.json (ch18 has only synoptic parallels — arrest, Peter's denial,
  Jesus before Pilate — not OT echoes; not absorbed into this script)
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (hagiazō, egō eimi, hypsōthēnai, basileia)

Key decisions in this range:
- Author referred to as "the Evangelist"; Jesus as "Jesus" or "the Son" — consistent with 12–13
- 17:1 ("the hour has come"): classified as direct revelation — the culminating Christological
  time-marker in John (cf. 2:4; 7:30; 8:20; 12:23); the prayer inaugurates the passion
- 17:3 ("that they know you... and Jesus Christ whom you have sent"): classified as direct
  revelation — Jesus uses his full title within the prayer; the definition of eternal life
  as knowledge of God through Christ is the Gospel's purpose statement
- 17:5 ("glory I had with you before the world began"): classified as direct revelation —
  explicit claim to pre-creation glory; the Prologue's theology spoken by the Son himself
- 17:19 ("for them I sanctify myself"): classified as direct revelation — hagiazō emauton
  is LXX priestly consecration language (Exod 28:41; Deut 15:19); the Son consecrates
  himself as both priest and sacrifice; this verse is the exegetical ground for calling
  ch17 the "High Priestly Prayer"
- 18:5-6 (egō eimi / soldiers fall): classified as direct revelation — the absolute egō
  eimi is the divine name (cf. 8:58; 13:19; LXX Isa 43:10); the prostration is the
  creaturely response to divine disclosure (cf. Dan 10:9; Rev 1:17)
- 18:9: classified as direct fulfillment — the Evangelist treats Jesus' own words (17:12)
  as Scripture already fulfilled
- 18:12 (Jesus bound): classified as revelation of God — shadow of Isaac's binding
  (Gen 22:9); the son bound for sacrifice at the father's command
- 18:14 (Caiaphas's role): classified as direct revelation — the Evangelist explicitly
  recalls 11:50-51; the high priest who prophesied the substitutionary death is the one
  arranging it
- 18:32: classified as direct fulfillment — the judicial transfer to Rome fulfills the
  hypsōthēnai predictions (3:14; 8:28; 12:32-33); the crucifixion (not stoning) is the
  scripturally required form of death
- 18:40 (Barabbas): classified as revelation of God — the guilty freed in place of the
  innocent; the Passover substitution in miniature; Barabbas (bar Abba = son of the
  father) as the guilty human freed by the death of the innocent Son of the Father
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "17": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "Father, the hour has come. Glorify your Son, that your Son may glorify you." The entire Gospel of John has been oriented toward this moment by the recurring deferral — "my hour has not yet come" (2:4; 7:30; 8:20) and its anticipation (12:23). Now, at the threshold of the passion, the hour arrives. The prayer frames the cross as mutual glorification: the Son glorifies the Father through obedience unto death; the Father glorifies the Son through the resurrection. What looks like defeat is the supreme disclosure of who the Father and the Son are.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "you granted him authority over all people that he might give eternal life to all those you have given him." The cosmic authority of the Son over all flesh is the Christological ground of the Gospel\'s universal mission. The scope is total — all flesh; the gift is the highest possible — eternal life; the recipients are those the Father has given the Son. This will become the explicit basis of the apostolic commission: "All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Therefore go and make disciples of all nations" (Matt 28:18–19).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "Now this is eternal life: that they know you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom you have sent." The Son defines eternal life as knowledge of God-in-Christ, and within the prayer names himself as "Jesus Christ" — the full Christological title. The formula is remarkable: he prays by naming himself as the object of the faith he is calling forth. The knowledge (<em>ginōskō</em>) is not intellectual acquaintance but relational-participatory union — the same word used of the Father knowing the Son (10:15). Eternal life is not an afterlife destination but a quality of relationship with God, available now through Christ.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have brought you glory on earth by finishing the work you gave me to do." The perfect tense (<em>eteleíōsa</em> — I have finished/completed) declares the incarnate mission accomplished, hours before the cross. The Evangelist consistently presents the cross not as the undoing of the ministry but as its completion — its <em>telos</em>. The "work" given by the Father runs from the Prologue through the signs and discourses; the cross is not an interruption but the apex. The Son reports completion before it is humanly visible, because the divine perspective on the mission is that it is already done.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "And now, Father, glorify me in your presence with the glory I had with you before the world began." The Son prays for the restoration of his pre-incarnate glory — "the glory I had," speaking from personal experience of a state before creation. This is the theological claim of the Prologue (1:1–2) now spoken as prayer: the incarnation was a voluntary entry into the creaturely sphere, and the resurrection-exaltation is the return to the eternal state. The "before the world began" (<em>pro katabolēs kosmou</em>) is the anchor of John\'s high Christology — the Son existed before and will exist beyond creation.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have revealed you to those whom you gave me out of the world." The Son\'s mission as the revealer of the Father — announced in the Prologue (1:18 — "he has made him known") — is here reported as completed. "I have manifested your name" (literal rendering of the Greek <em>ephanerōsa</em>) means the character, identity, and covenant faithfulness of the Father have been disclosed through the Son\'s person and work. The disciples are described as the Father\'s gift to the Son — a motif that recurs throughout this prayer (vv 2, 9, 24) and grounds the Son\'s intercession on their behalf.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now they know that everything you have given me comes from you." The disciples\' theological understanding — that the Son is the Father\'s representative, and that every word and work of the Son originates in the Father — is the fruit of the incarnate mission. Their knowledge is still partial; the full comprehension awaits the resurrection and the Spirit (14:26; 16:13). But the foundation is laid: they have received the Son as sent by the Father, which is the essential content of the faith the Gospel calls for.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "For I gave them the words you gave me and they accepted them. They knew with certainty that I came from you, and they believed that you sent me." The chain of divine communication — Father → Son → disciples — is the structure of all revelation in John. Christ\'s words are not his own (14:24 — "the words you hear are not my own; they belong to the Father who sent me") but are the Father\'s transmission through the Son. The disciples\' faith — that Jesus came from God and was sent by God — is the core Christological confession the Gospel asks of every reader.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "I pray for them. I am not praying for the world, but for those you have given me, for they are yours." The narrowing of the intercession to the disciples is not a denial of the Son\'s love for the world (3:16) but a specification of this prayer\'s scope. The disciples are the ones through whom the world will receive the Gospel (v20 — Jesus will pray for future believers through the disciples\' message). The priestly intercession is particular before it is universal: the Son prays first for those who will carry the word to the rest.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "All I have is yours, and all you have is mine. And glory has come to me through them." The mutual possessing of all things between Father and Son is the Christological statement of the Son\'s full divinity: to say "all you have is mine" is to claim co-equality with the Father. The glory coming to the Son through the disciples is the fruit of mission — their existence as believers is already the glorification of the one who called them. The mission to the disciples has been the Father\'s glory expressed through the Son\'s work.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "Holy Father, protect them by the power of your name, the name you gave me, so that they may be one as we are one." The address "Holy Father" is unique in the NT — the divine holiness grounds the appeal for the disciples\' protection. The name given to the Son (the divine name, which the Son has borne and revealed throughout John — 17:6; ego eimi in 8:58; 18:5–6) is the power that guards them. The unity prayed for — "as we are one" — takes the Trinitarian unity as both the model and the source of the church\'s unity.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "None has been lost except the one doomed to destruction so that Scripture would be fulfilled." The protection of the disciples during the earthly ministry is complete; Judas\'s loss is framed not as failure but as scriptural anticipation (Ps 41:9, cited in 13:18; cf. Ps 109:8 applied to Judas in Acts 1:20). The Evangelist consistently shows that every element of the passion — including the betrayal — was not an interruption of the Father\'s plan but woven into it before the foundation of the world. The exception confirms the rule: divine protection operates according to divine wisdom, not human calculation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "I say these things while I am still in the world, so that they may have the full measure of my joy within them." The joy of Christ — rooted in his unbroken communion with the Father — is offered as the disciples\' inheritance. The departing Son does not leave the disciples in fear; he leaves them in his joy, which the Spirit will sustain (15:11; 16:22–24). The cross that is hours away is approached in joy, not despair, because the Son sees beyond it to the resurrection and the homecoming to the Father\'s presence (v5). That joy is transferable to all who are united to him.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have given them your word and the world has hated them, for they are not of the world any more than I am of the world." The disciples\' alienation from the world is derived from and modeled on Christ\'s alienation from the world. The pattern of rejection that Jesus experienced (1:11 — "he came to his own, and his own did not receive him") is extended to the community of the Son. Receiving the divine word sets the disciples apart from the world\'s value system — not by religious separation but by the transformation that comes from hearing a different word than the world hears.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "My prayer is not that you take them out of the world but that you protect them from the evil one." The Son does not pray for his followers\' extraction from the dangerous world but for their protection within it. They are left in the world on mission (v18). The "evil one" (<em>ponēros</em>) — the power behind Judas\'s betrayal (13:2, 27) and the world\'s opposition — is a real adversary; the prayer for protection acknowledges the threat while asserting the Father\'s power over it. The disciples\' calling is presence-in-the-world, not escape from it.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "They are not of the world, even as I am not of it." The disciples\' not-belonging-to-the-world is derived from and shares in Christ\'s not-belonging. In John, the disciples\' identity is consistently defined by their union with the Son: they are what he is; they stand where he stands; they face what he faced. The Christological grounding of the church\'s distinct identity in the world is not a sociological description but a participation in the Son\'s own relationship to the created order — he is in the world but not sourced by it; they share that status by union with him.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "Sanctify them by the truth; your word is truth." The consecration (<em>hagiazō</em>) of the disciples through the divine word is the priestly application of the truth-theme that pervades John (8:32; 14:6). Since the Evangelist identifies Jesus as "the truth" (14:6), the prayer that the disciples be sanctified by truth is also a prayer that they be formed by and into Christ. The word that sanctifies is both the Scripture and the Son — the written word and the incarnate Word are inseparable instruments of the disciples\' consecration.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "As you sent me into the world, I have sent them into the world." The apostolic mission of the disciples derives from and mirrors the mission of the Son. The Son is the <em>apostellō</em> — the Sent One whose identity in John is inseparable from his being sent by the Father; now he himself sends, extending the Father\'s mission through him to the world through the disciples. The Great Commission (Matt 28:18–20) is the explicit command form of what is here stated as prayer. The disciples\' mission is the continuation and expression of the Son\'s own mission.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct revelation: "For them I sanctify myself, that they too may be truly sanctified." The key verse of the High Priestly Prayer: <em>hagiazō emauton</em> — "I sanctify/consecrate myself." The verb <em>hagiazō</em> is the LXX term for consecrating priests (Exod 28:41) and setting apart sacrificial offerings (Exod 13:2; Deut 15:19). The Son consecrates himself to the cross as simultaneously the priest who offers and the sacrifice offered. His self-consecration to death is the ground on which the disciples\' sanctification rests: they are made holy because he made himself holy for them. This single verse is the exegetical basis for calling John 17 the High Priestly Prayer — the priest consecrates the sacrifice, and the sacrifice is himself.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "My prayer is not for them alone. I pray also for those who will believe in me through their message." The prayer extends beyond the Eleven to all future believers — including those reading the Gospel. The Evangelist places the reader within the scope of the Son\'s intercession: John 17 is a prayer for every disciple who will come through the chain of apostolic witness. The church existed first in prayer before it existed in history. The Son\'s intercession for the not-yet-believing is the grace that undergirds the proclamation that will call them forth.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "that all of them may be one, Father, just as you are in me and I am in you. May they also be in us so that the world may believe that you have sent me." The unity for which the Son prays is defined by Trinitarian unity — the mutual indwelling of Father and Son (10:38; 14:10–11) is both the model and the basis for the community\'s unity. The purpose of unity is missional: so the world may believe the Son was sent. The fractured state of visible Christianity is the failure of the conditions this prayer requires; the prayer itself stands as the theological norm and the church\'s ongoing calling.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "I have given them the glory that you gave me, that they may be one as we are one." The glory given to the disciples is the shared relational life that belongs to those who are in Christ — not the divine nature itself but the participatory union with the Father that the Son possesses and shares. This is the Christological basis for what Eastern theology calls <em>theosis</em>: the believers\' participation in the divine life through union with the Son. The gift of glory is not an external reward but an interior sharing in what the Son has always had with the Father.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "I in them and you in me — so that they may be brought to complete unity. Then the world will know that you sent me and have loved them even as you have loved me." The chain of mutual indwelling — Father in Son, Son in disciples — is the structure of the new covenant community. The climactic claim is that the Father loves the disciples with the same love with which he loves the eternal Son. The love the Father has for the pre-existent Son (v24 — "because you loved me before the creation of the world") is extended to all who are united to the Son. This is the highest assertion of the believer\'s standing before God in the NT.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "Father, I want those you have given me to be with me where I am, and to see my glory, the glory you have given me because you loved me before the creation of the world." The Son\'s final petition is eschatological: the disciples\' ultimate destiny is to see his full unveiled glory. The love of the Father for the Son before creation (<em>pro katabolēs kosmou</em>) is the eternal foundation of everything — the glory, the mission, the disciples\' hope. The Beatific Vision — the face-to-face sight of the Son in his full glory — is what the disciples are headed toward. The prayer anchors their hope in the Father\'s pre-creation love.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "Righteous Father, though the world does not know you, I know you, and they know that you have sent me." The final address — "Righteous Father" — is the appeal to the divine character that ensures vindication of the Son and protection of the disciples. The righteousness of the Father will be demonstrated in the resurrection of the one the world condemned. The contrast between the world\'s ignorance and the disciples\' knowledge is the fruit of the Son\'s revelatory mission (1:18 — "no one has ever seen God, but the one and only Son... has made him known"). The Son alone bridges the gap between the unknowing world and the knowing Father.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "I have made you known to them, and will continue to make you known in order that the love you have for me may be in them and that I myself may be in them." The ongoing revelation of the Father through the Son — "will continue to make you known" — is the ministry the Spirit will carry forward (14:26; 16:13–15). The purpose of continued revelation is the inhabitation of the disciples by the divine love and by the Son himself. The prayer\'s final clause — "that I myself may be in them" — is the Evangelist\'s ultimate Christological statement: the Son abides in disciples as the Father abides in the Son (14:10). The prayer closes where the Gospel will end: the Son present in his people.</p>'
  },
  "18": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: crossing the Kidron Valley on the way to the garden invokes the OT shadow of David\'s crossing of the Kidron in flight from Absalom, his rebellious son (2 Sam 15:23) — the rightful king driven from the city by those who owed him loyalty, crossing the valley in sorrow. The Evangelist\'s geography is theologically precise: the Son, like the son of Jesse, leaves the city under threat from within his own people and crosses the valley that marks the boundary between Jerusalem and the Mount of Olives. The difference is that Jesus goes willingly toward what David fled from.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: Judas knows the garden because he has been a disciple — the intimacy that makes betrayal possible has been building since 13:2. He has sat at the table, received the foot-washing, heard the teaching, and now uses that proximity to deliver the Son to his enemies. Psalm 41:9 ("he who shared my bread has turned against me") — which the Evangelist cited in 13:18 as the scriptural anticipation of the betrayal — is enacted here with full geographical and relational specificity. The betrayal from within the circle of the beloved is the profoundest form of abandonment, and it is from within that the Son is delivered over.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: the combined force of Roman soldiers (<em>speira</em> — a detachment, possibly a cohort) and Jewish temple police, carrying torches and weapons, comes to arrest a single unarmed man. The Evangelist\'s understated presentation of the disproportion is the irony of the passion\'s opening: they bring light to find the Light of the world (1:9; 8:12); they bring weapons to take the Lamb who lays down his own life (10:17–18). The organized power of two empires — Roman military and Jewish priestly authority — is arrayed against the one who holds all authority over all flesh (17:2).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus, knowing all that was going to happen to him, went out." The divine foreknowledge that the Evangelist has attributed to Jesus throughout (2:25; 13:1, 3, 11) is stated explicitly — he knows everything that will happen and goes out to meet it rather than waiting to be found. The good shepherd who lays down his life actively (10:17–18 — "I lay it down of my own accord; no one takes it from me") does not retreat into the garden but steps forward to the arresting force. The question "Who is it you want?" is the shepherd interposing himself between the wolves and the flock.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: when Jesus says "I am he" (<em>egō eimi</em>), the Greek is the absolute form — the divine name. The same construction appears in 8:58 ("before Abraham was, I am"), 13:19 (announced as the sign of divine foreknowledge), and here at the arrest. What appears to be simple self-identification — "I am the one you\'re looking for" — is simultaneously the utterance of the name that belongs to the one who is, who was, and who is to come (Exod 3:14; Isa 43:10 LXX — "that you may know and believe me and understand that I am he"). Verse 6 shows that more than identification is occurring.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: the arresting party draws back and falls to the ground at the utterance of <em>egō eimi</em>. The physical prostration is the creaturely response to divine disclosure that appears throughout Scripture — Daniel falls on his face at the heavenly figure\'s words (Dan 10:9), Ezekiel falls prostrate before the divine glory (Ezek 1:28), John falls as dead at the glorified Son\'s feet (Rev 1:17). Those who have come to arrest the Son of God cannot arrest him; he must allow himself to be taken. The passion is not coercion but self-donation: the one who speaks the divine name chooses to lay it down.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: after the falling to the ground, Jesus asks again — "Who is it you want?" The Evangelist shows that the entire sequence remains under the Son\'s governance. He could have left as in 10:39 ("he escaped their grasp"); here he chooses to remain. The repetition of the question after the prostration is the Son re-establishing the arrest on his own terms, ensuring the disciples will escape (v8) before allowing himself to be taken. Every step of the passion is the Son\'s deliberate movement toward what he came for.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you are looking for me, then let these men go." The shepherd\'s substitutionary action is enacted before the cross: he offers himself so the sheep escape. The language echoes the Good Shepherd discourse (10:11–15 — "the good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep") and the prayer of 17:12 ("I protected them... none has been lost"). The gesture is the pastoral logic of the atonement in miniature: the one who is sought by judgment steps forward and says, in effect, let the others go.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct fulfillment: the Evangelist explicitly cites Jesus\' own words from 17:12 as Scripture being fulfilled — "I have not lost one of those you gave me." The Son\'s own word functions as prophetic Scripture, which the Evangelist has now seen fulfilled in the garden. The protection of the disciples in the arrest is the pastoral-eschatological promise kept: Jesus ensures his own are released before allowing the arrest to proceed. The fulfillment of his own words confirms that his promises carry the same authority as Scripture — because they are the Father\'s commands given through the Son (12:49–50).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: Peter\'s sword-stroke is the response of a disciple who does not yet understand what kind of king Jesus is or what kind of kingdom he brings. Peter believes the kingdom of Christ is defended by the violence of kingdoms that are of this world — the mistake the crowds made in 6:15 (wanting to make Jesus king by force). Jesus\' correction in v11 is the Christological definition: the cross is not a failure of the kingdom but its very means of establishment. Peter\'s sword and his imminent denial are both symptoms of the same misunderstanding that the resurrection will cure.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "Shall I not drink the cup the Father has given me?" The cup (<em>potērion</em>) is the cup of divine judgment that the Son drinks in place of his people — the image runs from Psalm 75:8 and Isaiah 51:17–22 through Jeremiah 25:15–16. The Synoptic Gethsemane prayer ("let this cup pass from me... yet not my will, but yours" — Matt 26:39) is compressed in John into a single rhetorical question that is its own answer: yes, the Son will drink it. He goes to the cross not as a victim of circumstances but as the one who accepts the appointed cup from the Father\'s hand.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God — shadow: "Then the detachment of soldiers with its commander and the Jewish officials arrested Jesus. They bound him." The binding of the Son of God — the one who has all authority over all flesh (17:2), at whose word the arresting party fell prostrate — is voluntary submission to creaturely constraint. The shadow behind the binding is the binding of Isaac (Gen 22:9), the son bound for sacrifice at the father\'s command. The Akedah and the passion share the same structural pattern: the father\'s will, the son\'s submission, the binding for sacrifice. What was stopped at the last moment in Genesis is carried through to completion here.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus is brought first to Annas, the former high priest whose political influence remained dominant. The true High Priest (Heb 4:14–16 — "we have a great high priest who has ascended into heaven, Jesus the Son of God") is being examined by a counterfeit one. The legitimate high priesthood of the Levitical covenant has been replaced by a political appointment backed by Roman power. The one who will supersede and fulfill everything the high priestly office was designed to anticipate stands before its corrupt human instantiation. The irony is structural and Christological.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: the Evangelist explicitly recalls 11:50–51 — the unwitting prophecy of Caiaphas, who as high priest that year prophesied that "it would be good if one man died for the people." The Evangelist had already noted (11:51) that this was not Caiaphas\'s own idea but a prophecy from his high priestly office. Now, as Jesus is brought to Caiaphas, the reader is reminded: the one who pronounced the substitutionary principle is the one through whom the substitution is being arranged. The high priest\'s office is designed to anticipate the one sacrifice that fulfills all sacrifices; its last holder is orchestrating that sacrifice without understanding what he is doing.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "another disciple" known to the high priest — traditionally identified with the Beloved Disciple, the eyewitness authority behind the Gospel (21:24) — enters the courtyard with Jesus while Peter waits outside. The Beloved Disciple\'s presence means the trial narrative is eyewitness testimony at the highest level of access. The contrast between the Beloved Disciple (who enters and observes) and Peter (who waits and then denies) is the Evangelist\'s portrait of two kinds of proximity to Christ: one that endures through suffering and one that fails under social pressure.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: Peter\'s entry into the courtyard is made possible by the Beloved Disciple — the one with access enabling the one who lags. The architecture of the scene is the Evangelist\'s: the gate, the servant girl, the fire in the courtyard, the waiting Peter — all elements in the portrait of a disciple who has placed himself at the scene of the denial he is about to make. Peter wants to be near Christ but cannot sustain that nearness under pressure. His presence in the courtyard is courageous; his three denials will be its collapse.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: the first denial — "I am not" (<em>ouk eimi</em>) — is the inversion of the divine name that Jesus has just spoken in the garden (18:5–6, <em>egō eimi</em>). The Son who declares the divine name is denied by the disciple who says "I am not." The Evangelist does not editorialize on the denial; the structural irony carries the theological weight. Peter denies being a disciple of "this man" — the distancing language is immediate. The one who swore to lay down his life (13:37) begins the three-stage process of disowning the one for whom he claimed he would die.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: Peter stands warming himself at a fire built by "the servants and officials" — those who have arrested Jesus and will participate in his condemnation. The detail is precise and deliberate: Peter\'s warmth comes from the enemies\' fire; his presence is among the enemies\' company. The fire that warms him is the fire by whose light he will be recognized (v26) and by whose warmth he will complete his denials. The Evangelist shows a disciple who has not taken flight but cannot hold his ground — half-committed, warming himself in the wrong company at the wrong fire.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: the high priest questions Jesus about his disciples and his teaching — seeking to implicate a movement and extract seditious content. The true High Priest stands before the false one. The interrogation is revealing: the high priest of the Levitical order interrogates the one whose teaching is the Father\'s own command (12:49–50 — "the Father who sent me commanded me what to say") and whose disciples are those given him by the Father (17:2, 6). He is being questioned about the divine revelation he has transmitted without concealment or distortion.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct revelation: "I have spoken openly to the world... I said nothing in secret." The Son\'s testimony about his ministry is the testimony of the one who is the truth: everything said was said publicly, in the synagogues and temple where all could hear. There is no hidden seditious teaching, no underground movement. The claim to transparency is simultaneously the claim to be the light that has nothing to conceal (3:20–21 — "everyone who does evil hates the light... but whoever lives by the truth comes into the light"). The one who is light incarnate has no secret life that contradicts his public one.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "Why question me? Ask those who heard me." The Son\'s legal challenge is both procedurally correct — due process requires witnesses, not self-incrimination — and theologically significant: the witnesses to Christ\'s teaching are the many who heard him publicly. Their testimony would validate the mission. The challenge also exposes the illegitimacy of the proceeding: Annas has no intention of summoning witnesses, because the trial is not a search for truth but a predetermined condemnation being given a legal form.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: the official\'s slap is illegal — striking a defendant who has not been convicted is due-process violation, as Jesus points out in v23. The Son of God is struck by a minor official; the Judge of all the earth submits to illegal violence from one of his creatures. The Evangelist does not dramatize the moment but reports it plainly, which is more devastating: the one who has authority over all flesh (17:2) submits to a slap in a kangaroo proceeding. This is the voluntary humiliation of the passion, the incarnation of the Servant who "offered my back to those who beat me" (Isa 50:6).</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "If I said something wrong, testify as to what is wrong. But if I spoke the truth, why did you strike me?" The Son\'s response is the response of one who is the truth — calm, precise, legally exact, and unanswerable. He does not retaliate; he does not capitulate; he simply points to what a just proceeding would require. The rhetorical question — "why did you strike me?" — is the question that will be answered by the resurrection: the one struck is vindicated; the one who struck is without defense. Truth that is silenced by violence is truth vindicated by the empty tomb.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus is sent from Annas to Caiaphas, moving from hand to hand through the priestly establishment. The Son who has said "I have come to testify to the truth" (18:37) is passed along by those who have no use for truth and no standing to judge the one who is it. Each transfer — Annas to Caiaphas, Caiaphas to Pilate (v28) — is another link in the chain of the passion that the Evangelist presents as governed not by Jewish and Roman decision but by the Father\'s will being worked through human instruments. The Son is moved; the Son is also in control.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: the second denial by Peter — "I am not" (<em>ouk eimi</em>) — echoes the first (v17). The repetition of the inverted divine name is the Evangelist\'s quiet structuring of Peter\'s failure against Christ\'s declaration. Three times Jesus has said <em>egō eimi</em> (6:20; 8:58; 18:5–6); three times Peter will say <em>ouk eimi</em>. The man warming himself at the enemies\' fire will be denied three times before the rooster crows — and will be restored three times by the risen Lord who asks "do you love me?" (21:15–17). The denials are not the last word about Peter.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: the third challenge comes from a relative of Malchus — one who was in the garden and witnessed the sword-stroke (v10). The circle of evidence tightens around Peter: "didn\'t I see you with him in the garden?" This is eyewitness testimony to Peter\'s presence with Jesus at the arrest. The Evangelist\'s precision — "a relative of the man whose ear Peter had cut off" — suggests eyewitness sourcing (possibly the Beloved Disciple who was also in the courtyard). Every detail closes off Peter\'s escape routes, making the third denial the most exposed and therefore the most decisive.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: the rooster\'s crow at Peter\'s third denial fulfills Jesus\' specific prediction (13:38 — "before the rooster crows, you will disown me three times"). The fulfillment of the prediction does not condemn Peter but confirms the divine foreknowledge the Son has exercised throughout the passion narrative. Every human failure — Judas\'s betrayal, the disciples\' flight (16:32), Peter\'s denial — was anticipated, incorporated into the Son\'s knowledge, and used within the Father\'s plan. The rooster does not sound the death of Peter\'s discipleship; it sounds the reliability of the Son\'s word. The restoration of 21:15–17 is already implicit in the foreknowledge of 13:38.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: the Evangelist\'s irony at its most acute: those who will not enter the praetorium to avoid ritual defilement — so that they can eat the Passover — are in that same act arranging the death of the Passover Lamb. They preserve the outer shell of Passover purity while committing the act that the Passover was always designed to anticipate and fulfill. The Passover they are preparing to eat will be the last Passover before the one whom all Passovers foreshadow is sacrificed. Their scrupulous avoidance of the Gentile palace door is the measure of how completely they have missed who is standing in front of them.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: Pilate\'s emergence to meet the Jewish leaders — a concession to their purity concerns — places the Roman governor in a liminal position throughout the trial: between justice and political pressure, between what he knows is right and what the crowd demands. His question "What charges are you bringing?" is the question that will never receive a satisfying answer. The Evangelist will demonstrate through the Roman trial that the charge against Jesus cannot be stated in terms that constitute a genuine crime, because the Son has done nothing wrong. The trial is the vindication of innocence conducted as the condemnation of guilt.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: the non-answer — "if he were not a criminal, we would not have handed him over" — exposes the legal circularity of the proceeding. There is no specified charge; there is only the assertion of guilt by those who have determined the outcome in advance. The Evangelist uses the Jewish leaders\' inability to articulate a crime as the structural argument of the trial: the one being condemned is innocent, and every participant in the proceeding who is honest will confirm it (Pilate three times — vv 38, 19:4, 19:6; Pilate\'s wife — Matt 27:19; Judas himself — Matt 27:3–4).</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: the Jewish leaders\' objection — "we have no right to execute anyone" — is the Evangelist\'s explanation of why the mode of death must be Roman crucifixion rather than Jewish stoning. The transfer of jurisdiction is not bureaucratic accident but divine necessity: the Son must be "lifted up" (<em>hypsōthēnai</em> — 3:14; 8:28; 12:32–33), which requires a Roman cross. Jewish execution by stoning would not fulfill the prediction. The machinery of Roman-Jewish political friction is the instrument by which the specific form of death required by Scripture is accomplished.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "This took place to fulfill what Jesus had said about the kind of death he was going to die." The Evangelist explicitly identifies the judicial transfer as the fulfillment of the hypsōthēnai predictions — being "lifted up" (3:14; 8:28; 12:32–33). Crucifixion on a Roman cross, not stoning, is the required form; the Son\'s own words required it, the Scripture behind those words anticipated it (Num 21:8–9 — the bronze serpent lifted up; Isa 52:13 — "raised and lifted up"), and the political mechanics of competing jurisdictions is the instrument of its accomplishment. The cross is not Roman legal procedure; it is Christological necessity.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct revelation: Pilate\'s first question — "Are you the king of the Jews?" — is the Christological question the entire Gospel has been building toward. Nathanael asked it at the beginning (1:49 — "Rabbi, you are the King of Israel"); the crowd attempted to force the answer (6:15 — wanting to make him king by force); the triumphal entry enacted it (12:13–15). Now the Roman governor asks it directly, and the Son\'s answer will be the most theologically compressed statement of his kingdom in the Gospel. The question every character in John has faced takes its most direct form in the praetorium.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: the counter-question — "Is that your own idea, or did others talk to you about me?" — is the Son\'s pastoral diagnostic. Pilate\'s question could arise from genuine seeking or from inherited political anxiety about a Jewish messianic figure. The Son wants to know which, because the two questions require different answers. The question also exposes the borrowed nature of the charge: Pilate is asking someone else\'s question, framed in someone else\'s theological categories, for someone else\'s purposes. The Roman governor is functioning as an instrument of a proceeding he does not understand.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "Am I a Jew?" — Pilate\'s dismissal of the messianic category reveals how entirely he misses what he is dealing with. He asks "What have you done?" looking for a Roman crime. He will find none: v38 will be his verdict ("I find no basis for a charge against him"). But the irony of the question is Johannine and pointed: the right answer to "What have you done?" is everything — "I have created the world, revealed the Father, healed the sick, raised the dead, and am about to lay down my life for the world." Pilate asks the right question and cannot receive the full answer.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "My kingdom is not of this world." The definitive Christological statement of the nature and origin of Christ\'s kingdom: it is real — Jesus does not deny being a king — but it is not <em>from</em> this world (<em>ouk estin ek tou kosmou toutou</em> — not sourced in, not sustained by, not operating by the logic of worldly power). The proof he offers is the absence of armed resistance: if it were a worldly kingdom, there would be violence in its defense. The kingdom of Christ advances not by coercion but by witness (v37), not by swords but by the truth. The cross is the paradoxical throne of a king who rules by dying.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "The reason I was born and came into the world is to testify to the truth. Everyone on the side of truth listens to me." The Son defines his kingship as the embodiment and testimony of truth — his reign is the reign of reality over falsehood, light over darkness. The incarnation is purposive: he was born for this, came into the world for this. The claim that "everyone on the side of truth listens to me" is the Christological principle of the Gospel: the sheep hear the shepherd\'s voice (10:3–4, 27); those who are of the truth recognize truth when it speaks. The kingdom of Christ is constituted by those who hear and receive the true word.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: "What is truth?" — Pilate\'s question is the most famous unanswered question in Scripture, and the Evangelist\'s silence is the most eloquent response. The Truth is standing in front of Pilate; the answer to the question is the person asking it. Pilate turns and walks away without waiting for an answer — the portrait of the one who encounters truth and cannot receive it. His verdict ("I find no basis for a charge against him") is the judicial confirmation of what the Gospel has been saying: the Son is innocent; the proceeding against him is a failure of justice. Truth vindicated by Pilate\'s own mouth, even as Pilate walks away from it.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: the Passover amnesty — the custom of releasing a prisoner at the festival — becomes the mechanism of substitution. One is released; one is condemned. The custom is the Passover principle in administrative form: one set free while another bears the penalty. The crowd\'s choice between Jesus and Barabbas is the choice between the innocent and the guilty, the righteous and the condemned, the Lamb and the rebel. The custom that was meant to honor the feast of liberation is being used to accomplish the greatest act of injustice while the greatest act of liberation — the cross — is being arranged.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: Barabbas — guilty of insurrection, the very charge implicitly leveled at Jesus — is released while the innocent Son is condemned. The Evangelist\'s note that Barabbas "had taken part in an uprising" is the final irony: the one genuinely guilty of political revolt goes free; the one who said "my kingdom is not of this world" is executed as a political rebel. The name Barabbas (<em>bar Abba</em> — "son of the father" in Aramaic) adds a layer of Christological irony: the human "son of the father," guilty and condemned, is freed by the death of the divine Son of the Father, innocent and condemned in his place. The substitution of the passion is anticipated in the Barabbas exchange.</p>'
  }
}

